<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>She visited the family on Monday with Busi Shiba, Mpumalanga’s social development MEC, to provide support. Municipal workers found Xolani’s grave violated. It was found that both his hands and his left leg had been cut off. Bogopane-Zulu told the family the unveiling of the tombstone would be part of their programme to raise awareness against the killings of people living with albinism.“Whenever members of the community pass there, it will serve as a special reminder of what happened,” she said. The deputy minister said they would provide the family with all the necessary support. Xolani’s aunt Thembi Mtuta said the family was comforted by the deputy minister’s visit. “We are happy with what we agreed on and we hope it will work.” The date for the unveiling of the tombstone hasn’t been announced yet.